1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,248
Two answers to the same question,

2
00:00:02,248 --> 00:00:04,872
in identical confident sentences, side by side.

3
00:00:04,872 --> 00:00:06,746
One of them is wrong.

4
00:00:06,746 --> 00:00:09,745
Looking at the page, you cannot tell which.

5
00:00:09,745 --> 00:00:13,118
> This isn't a failure mode unique to AI.

6
00:00:13,118 --> 00:00:16,117
Confident humans get things wrong all the time.

7
00:00:16,117 --> 00:00:19,490
But with a model, the confidence is essentially free.

8
00:00:19,490 --> 00:00:22,488
It costs the model nothing to sound sure.

9
00:00:22,488 --> 00:00:25,112
So a sentence that sounds sure is

10
00:00:25,112 --> 00:00:26,986
almost no evidence at all.

11
00:00:26,986 --> 00:00:30,359
> If the confidence isn't the signal, what is?

12
00:00:30,359 --> 00:00:32,225
There are four quadrants here.

13
00:00:32,225 --> 00:00:35,956
> Confident and right — that's what we hope for.

14
00:00:35,956 --> 00:00:39,313
A lot of the time, that's what we get.

15
00:00:39,313 --> 00:00:42,671
> Hedging and right — slightly annoying, but honest.

16
00:00:42,671 --> 00:00:45,282
The kind of behavior we should want

17
00:00:45,282 --> 00:00:47,148
models to do more of.

18
00:00:47,148 --> 00:00:50,505
> Hedging and wrong — visible, easy to ignore.

19
00:00:50,505 --> 00:00:53,490
> And the dangerous quadrant: confident and wrong.

20
00:00:53,490 --> 00:00:56,474
Confident-and-wrong looks identical, on the page, to confident-and-right.

21
00:00:56,474 --> 00:00:59,459
Same syntax, same tone, same little explanatory paragraph.

22
00:00:59,459 --> 00:01:03,563
> So the goal isn't to read the model's tone harder.

23
00:01:03,563 --> 00:01:06,174
The goal is to do something the

24
00:01:06,174 --> 00:01:08,040
model can't do for you.

25
00:01:08,039 --> 00:01:09,126
The simplest test.

26
00:01:09,126 --> 00:01:10,938
The one most people skip.

27
00:01:10,938 --> 00:01:12,749
> Look at the answer.

28
00:01:12,749 --> 00:01:15,647
Find a specific factual claim — a date,

29
00:01:15,647 --> 00:01:19,632
a paper title, a formula, a function name, a quoted sentence.

30
00:01:19,632 --> 00:01:22,168
Something you could verify in thirty seconds.

31
00:01:22,168 --> 00:01:23,979
> Check that one thing.

32
00:01:23,979 --> 00:01:26,877
> If it's right, you've learned a little.

33
00:01:26,877 --> 00:01:29,413
If it's wrong, you've learned a lot.

34
00:01:29,413 --> 00:01:31,949
Because every unverifiable claim sitting next to

35
00:01:31,949 --> 00:01:34,485
a wrong verifiable one should drop in

36
00:01:34,485 --> 00:01:37,021
your trust by roughly the same amount.

37
00:01:37,021 --> 00:01:39,556
> A good rule of thumb: if

38
00:01:39,556 --> 00:01:42,817
two of three checkable claims in the answer fail,

39
00:01:42,817 --> 00:01:46,439
treat the entire answer as a draft, not a result.

40
00:01:46,439 --> 00:01:47,244
Second test.

41
00:01:47,244 --> 00:01:50,060
Ask the model: "What would change your

42
00:01:50,060 --> 00:01:53,279
answer?" > A well-calibrated reply names an updater.

43
00:01:53,279 --> 00:01:56,095
Something like: "If the paper I'm citing

44
00:01:56,095 --> 00:01:59,716
turns out to be from 2019 instead of 2021,

45
00:01:59,716 --> 00:02:03,739
I'm wrong about the precedent." That's a real, falsifiable hook.

46
00:02:03,739 --> 00:02:06,556
> An overconfident reply just restates the

47
00:02:06,556 --> 00:02:10,981
original claim with more words, or says nothing would change it.

48
00:02:10,981 --> 00:02:13,797
> Saying nothing would change it is

49
00:02:13,797 --> 00:02:16,614
almost never correct about an empirical question.

50
00:02:16,614 --> 00:02:18,625
When you hear that pattern,

51
00:02:18,625 --> 00:02:21,442
you've found an answer the model isn't

52
00:02:21,442 --> 00:02:23,855
actually examining — it's just defending.

53
00:02:23,855 --> 00:02:24,744
Third test.

54
00:02:24,744 --> 00:02:27,855
Don't ask "are there hedges in this

55
00:02:27,855 --> 00:02:30,966
answer." Ask "are the hedges in the

56
00:02:30,966 --> 00:02:33,632
right places." > Compare two paragraphs.

57
00:02:33,632 --> 00:02:36,743
> Paragraph A: "It's possible that X

58
00:02:36,743 --> 00:02:39,409
may arguably perhaps be the case,

59
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:43,853
and we might potentially think Y could hold." Hedges everywhere.

60
00:02:43,853 --> 00:02:44,742
Hedge inflation.

61
00:02:44,742 --> 00:02:49,186
That paragraph isn't more honest — it's just less committed.

62
00:02:49,186 --> 00:02:53,185
> Paragraph B: makes confident claims about well-known facts,

63
00:02:53,185 --> 00:02:56,296
and concentrates its hedges on the dates,

64
00:02:56,296 --> 00:02:59,851
attributions, and edge cases where uncertainty actually lives.

65
00:02:59,851 --> 00:03:01,628
That paragraph is calibrated.

66
00:03:01,628 --> 00:03:03,850
> Sprinkled hedges aren't honesty.

67
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:05,183
Concentrated hedges are.

68
00:03:05,183 --> 00:03:08,958
A fourth test, for when the stakes are higher.

69
00:03:08,958 --> 00:03:13,572
The diagnostic from the previous video, brought into a single conversation.

70
00:03:13,572 --> 00:03:16,927
> Take your question and ask it twice,

71
00:03:16,927 --> 00:03:19,024
with mild changes in phrasing.

72
00:03:19,024 --> 00:03:21,960
Not the content — just the wording.

73
00:03:21,960 --> 00:03:24,896
"What year was MMLU introduced?" versus "When

74
00:03:24,896 --> 00:03:27,832
did the MMLU benchmark first appear?" >

75
00:03:27,832 --> 00:03:30,768
A calibrated model gives the same answer

76
00:03:30,768 --> 00:03:33,703
with the same hedges in both runs.

77
00:03:33,703 --> 00:03:35,800
> An uncalibrated one shifts.

78
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:38,736
Confident two thousand twenty in one phrasing.

79
00:03:38,736 --> 00:03:41,672
Hedged "around 2020 or 2021" in another.

80
00:03:41,672 --> 00:03:44,608
A different year entirely in a third.

81
00:03:44,608 --> 00:03:47,963
That instability isn't visible inside any one response.

82
00:03:47,963 --> 00:03:50,060
It's only visible across runs.

83
00:03:50,060 --> 00:03:52,996
> Same logic as benchmark rerun spread,

84
00:03:52,996 --> 00:03:56,352
applied to the chat in front of you.

85
00:03:56,352 --> 00:03:59,095
So, three questions to carry with you.

86
00:03:59,095 --> 00:04:01,054
Four if you have time.

87
00:04:01,054 --> 00:04:01,838
> One.

88
00:04:01,838 --> 00:04:04,581
Pick a verifiable claim, and verify it.

89
00:04:04,581 --> 00:04:08,891
If it fails, every unverifiable claim near it should lose weight.

90
00:04:08,891 --> 00:04:09,675
> Two.

91
00:04:09,675 --> 00:04:12,026
Ask: what would change your answer?

92
00:04:12,026 --> 00:04:14,377
If you don't get an updater,

93
00:04:14,377 --> 00:04:16,729
you didn't get a calibrated answer.

94
00:04:16,729 --> 00:04:17,512
> Three.

95
00:04:17,512 --> 00:04:19,080
Look at the hedges.

96
00:04:19,080 --> 00:04:21,431
Are they concentrated where uncertainty lives,

97
00:04:21,431 --> 00:04:23,782
or sprinkled uniformly to soften everything?

98
00:04:23,782 --> 00:04:26,525
> And the bonus fourth: re-ask the

99
00:04:26,525 --> 00:04:28,485
question in a different phrasing.

100
00:04:28,485 --> 00:04:31,228
If the answer drifts, your real uncertainty

101
00:04:31,228 --> 00:04:34,363
is wider than the model is showing you.

102
00:04:34,363 --> 00:04:36,714
> If two of these fail,

103
00:04:36,714 --> 00:04:39,849
the right move isn't to ignore the answer.

104
00:04:39,849 --> 00:04:44,160
It's to drop your confidence in it, and go check more.

105
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:47,011
Confidence in a sentence is a font choice.

106
00:04:47,011 --> 00:04:49,506
Correctness is something you have to check.

107
00:04:49,506 --> 00:04:51,288
> The good news is,

108
00:04:51,288 --> 00:04:54,496
you only have to check enough — not everything.

109
00:04:54,496 --> 00:04:55,566
One verifiable claim.

110
00:04:55,566 --> 00:04:56,279
One updater.

111
00:04:56,279 --> 00:04:58,061
One look at the hedges.

112
00:04:58,061 --> 00:05:01,982
Three small habits that catch most of the high-stakes confident-wrong cases.

113
00:05:01,982 --> 00:05:04,477
> This is the third in a

114
00:05:04,477 --> 00:05:06,616
small series on reading AI honestly.

115
00:05:06,616 --> 00:05:08,398
Links to the others below.

116
00:05:08,398 --> 00:05:10,893
> The story behind the headline keeps

117
00:05:10,893 --> 00:05:13,032
being a useful place to look.
